The Hospital Patient Management System is a console-based software application developed in C++ to automate and
streamline the process of managing patient records in a hospital or clinic environment.
The system leverages fundamental data structures, specifically arrays for storing patient records and a queue for managing the patient waiting list, 
to deliver efficient and reliable operations.

The application enables hospital staff to perform four core operations: adding new patients to the system,
viewing the complete list of registered patients, searching for a specific patient by their unique ID, and deleting patient records when required.
Each patient record stores essential information including a unique patient ID, the patient's full name, and age.

By eliminating manual paperwork and reducing human error, the system improves accuracy and efficiency in patient data management. 
The queue-based waiting list ensures that patients are attended to in the order they arrive, maintaining fairness and organization.
The use of arrays allows quick indexed access and efficient record management within a bounded capacity.

Overall, this project demonstrates the practical application of data structures in solving real-world healthcare management problems while providing a clean,
menu-driven interface that is easy to use even with limited technical knowledge.
